# Architecture & Development Workflow

## 1. Project Structure (Next.js App Router)
- **`app/`**: Core directory for Pages and APIs following Next.js standards (`page.tsx`, `layout.tsx`, `loading.tsx`).
  - `app/api/`: Server-side API endpoints.
  - `app/results/[runId]/`: Dynamic routes for user dashboard results.
  - `app/results/[runId]/print/`: Optimized printing-only routes.
- **`components/`**: Reusable React components (Charts, UI, Flow Sections).
- **`lib/`**: Utilities (formatters), Global Configuration (`neurologicalConfig.ts`), and constants.

## 2. TypeScript Standards
- Prefer **`interface`** for stable object definitions (Tests, Steps, RunData).
- Every API response must have a clean interface definition for frontend safety.
- Avoid **`any`** at all costs. Strictly type sensitive data like trajectories.

## 3. Dependency Management
- **Next.js Config**: Update `serverExternalPackages` in `next.config.mjs` for server-side libraries like `puppeteer-core` and `@sparticuz/chromium`.
- **Package.json**: Verify chromium-pack compatibility before upgrading dependencies.

## 4. Deployment & Reliability (Vercel)
- Manage all sensitive environment variables on the Vercel Dashboard.
- **Preview Staging**: Verify font and chart rendering on Vercel Preview before merging to Production.
- **Branding**: Update `/app/icon.png` to auto-generate Favicons synchronously across all pages.

## 5. Persistence & Mocking
- Results Storage: Use external databases (if available) or a stable mock engine to avoid disrupting the user experience during testing.
